Just finished an older 30 Days version and found it very beneficial for regaining strength and flexibility that was laying dormant. Took a day off before embarking on this one as I had doubled up a few days in the previous one trying to gain too much too quick and regressed a little in the hip flexibility I had achieved. Note to self, slow and steady. My objectives here are to eliminate lower back pain, gain body alignment, synergy, strength and flexibility and be mindful of every activity. I find conscious thought of the tight area while stretching really works. Relaxing the tension with thought and focused breathing, I can feel the release. I am so much more nimble throughout my daily life, sitting cross legged more often than not, even at work. Flipping light switches with my feet. Belly has gone down quite a bit as I have changed my eating habits too. Most challenging things were the balance postures which I thought were my strength, spine rolling and I Lulued my lemons in the closed knee child's pose a couple of times. Super impressed with progress overall after just 30 days at 58 years of age. I'll be doing hand stands by spring! Thanks Adriene and Benji!

Hi everyone! I just need to get some things off my chest right now. 
I'm pregnant for the first time (week 16) and it has been really difficult so far. I am quite isolated, in lock down, because of COVID, unable to see friends and family other than my spouse. I've also had pretty bad pregnancy symptoms, non-stop nausea and tiredness, for months now. It's much harder than I anticipated. I've been really sedentary for the past two months, because even getting up was difficult and caused me to retch. 
I'm usually quite active, I walk a lot, hike, run, do yoga very often and climb... but it's really hard for me to start over now... I think I'm a bit depressed because of the symptoms, the inactivity, and the isolation... Also, even though I'm very happy and I've been looking forward to be a mom, this pregnancy was not planned, and me and my spouse are both still students, so there's been some other negative emotions involved as well... I thought I still had a couple of years before becoming a mom to get ready psychologically and feel stable. It's very scary, honestly. 
Now, I'm still exhausted, but my nausea is starting to go away a bit, so I'm trying this out. Yesterday, I redid yoga for the first time in 2 months, and it felt very good. I faced my fears of not being ready to become a mom and cried a lot, and held myself. Hopefully I can win over my inner demons and make it to day 30. Send me good vibes. I think I will need it.
Love you all xxx And thank you Adriene for everything you're doing, you're wonderful. Namaste.

Darn it Adriene! I just finished your 2015 '30 days of yoga' videos, managed to make it through without shedding a tear. And then here, day 1, BAM! Cried throughout the whole video. Recognise. I recognised frustration, and I don't like feeling frustrated (who does, eh?), and that creates tension and sadness. And at the same time, at the end of the video, you mentioned: connect to your true/best self, and recognise it in others. It's so easy to stay in the frustration, the sadness, I can make myself into a victim of my own life. But in the end it's more helpful to recognise I DO have control, every morning again. I can't change what happened in the past and the future is yet unborn. "Therefore, the present moment is the only real moment and it's only in the present moment that a conscious contact with God can be found!"¬†Every morning I have the choice to focus on what I CAN control, on the things that ARE present in my life, in the relationships I DO have with people around me. I struggle with that sometimes, but it will more positively affect the world around me when I learn to recognise my sadness, allow it time to be present, to be able to release it, to make space for joy and love. Have a great day, whoever reads this.
http://www.justloveaudio.com/resources/12_Steps_Recovery/Step_10_11/Effective_Prayer_Meditation.pdf

Doing this yoga practice for the 4th time.
 First time was in January during my entrance exams and finals, this helped me a lot with stress and to relax in between study sessions. I actively began to apply Adrienne's advice in day to day life, the most powerful one being  : "let your breath do the work for you." In February during a revision class I suddenly experienced intense stomach ache, normally I would have immediately voiced my discomfort but this time my first response was to concentrate on controlled, deep breathing. While in the infirmary, I started slow breathing exercise, and I could hear Adrienne's voice saying "just one more, you got this." 
Hearing that, I continued to do so. It was during this time I experienced my first "awakening moment." After ending my first whole 30 day practice, I didn't feel divine or awakened or anything, I wondered how come I am not experiencing any of those moments other people keep commenting under every video. But after a few days of not continuing yoga, I realised how much more flexible I have become, and how doing yoga in the evenings, after the day almost ended, helped me to unwind. It wasn't to feel anything special or connected to the divine being, but to myself and my body. It was about calmness and serenity and peace.
Each time I repeat this routine, I get better and feel better. Hearing your words of encouragement, I feel amazing, not immediately, but when I am in pain, it is your voice I hear. The infirmary incident had me placing my full trust in you. I could only hear your words in my head telling me I got this.
Thank you so much for helping me achieve this, Adrienne‚ù§Ô∏è

To anyone starting/doing this practice, welcome home! So happy for you and your journey. Like Adrienne says, move like you love your body‚ù§Ô∏è

That was a great class. Calming and centreing, yet energising. I completed the '30 days of yoga with Adrienne' over the weekend, and was delighted to find another 'Home' 30 day course to follow. I am/was an off/on yoga practitioner, experiencing difficulty in maintaining a self home practice. Have been practising Iyengar Yoga at regular classes for about 12 years, having started at the tender age of 48, and then self home practice for the past 7 years which , as I say, I have been struggling with. I am now 67 years old. Discovering Yoga with Adrienne has restored my enthusiasm for a regular practice, offering me a sense of inner balance that I value. I sometimes supplement the classes with additional poses: inversions or range of standing postures etc. Sometimes not. That is the beauty of these classes: they are entirely accessible, for both less and more experienced yogis. Each to their own level. I appreciate the discipline, guidance and variation of instruction, and feel enriched by the quality of serenity Adrienne brings to her teaching. The value is in the inspiration to return, get on the mat, and give yourself over to it.

Constructive criticism time. 

You don‚Äôt break down the language for the newbies. You have a hard time explaining what you are doing and how you modify movements in the downward dog for example. 

Furthermore there seems to be an awful lot of filler conversation. People that I have seen try these exercises tend to lose interest due to too much pointless pondering of existence conversation and too little breakdown of the movements. 

This is one of the reasons why I appreciate Gaiam‚Äôs instructional exercise videos, because they treat you like you aren‚Äôt a Yogi with 10 years of experience, they break down the movements, explain the positions as well as the tensions and sensation you will PHYSICALLY feel in your body, provide multiple camera angles of the positions ( which in addition helps prevent injury, an exercise professional should know better ) and they don‚Äôt ramble on about inconsequential background noise thoughts. 

There are my two cents regarding this series. It may work for some but video views do not translate into positive experiences. What about likes, aren‚Äôt they a good indicator? Not really, not unless you have a million likes. Right now you have less likes than people that have died globally from Covid-19. Not a good indicator. 

For the people having trouble understanding the language and techniques, try Gaiam‚Äôs series instead. They instruct you like its your first time and are very patient.

I've been really wanting to get into yoga  but also just to do something to help myself, help my body--from the inside out. To ease the anxiety and give myself some love so that I can spread spread spread kindness and love to others. (It's funny, I used to be so skeptical when people who were passionate about it said how good it felt. I'm not a flexible person, and even basic poses are challenging for me). But recently, I've dabbled in it a bit, and found that as long as I truly put effort in--moving my body with my breaths even when I can't fully do a pose, I HAVE gained this sense of awareness with in my body. I feel looser, I feel more conscious when I bend down to the ground or stretch up to reach a cupboard. And I do believe that these breaths and thoughts help ease my anxiety. I am so happy that I was able to do this practice today!! I woke up this morning feeling kind of sad, and my awareness of this made me actually get emotional during this session :'). I don't know. It felt special. I really, really home that I can make it all the way through these HOME videos, and continue to actually make yoga part of my daily routine. Thank you so much, Adriene, for making these videos. I can feel your kindness, empathy, and care. <3

Hi Adriene (and all the lovely folks here!) I wanted to say that I am very excited about these thirty days of home practice, and I am so grateful to have found this space. 2019 was one of the most challenging of my life, and while I'm under no illusions that all can be fixed at once, finding YWA and slowing growing a daily practice is one of the most valuable discoveries I made that year, and that I take with me into this next year, and decade. Practicing at home, but still with a feeling of connectivity to this community has been immensely helpful when I have felt isolated yet unable to leave my own home. It has helped me not to fear looking inwards, but being open to what I might find there, and to deal with whatever I encounter. Thank you for guiding me, and this community, with such grace and humour (and an adorable dog!), it is incredible valuable work that you do. Happy New Year everyone!

I'm a bit apprehensive about the fact that the mention that this series will pick up the pace came in right about that time :/

The word yoga is derived from the Sanskrit word "yujir yoge" which means to join, unite, meet, etc.  Therefore, yoga means the meeting of the soul with the divine (one has to know that the soul is part of the divine).  According to another sense, yoga is derived from "Yuj Samadhau", because even in the state of Samadhi, there is a unification of soul and God, so both have the same meaning.

I love you oh so much for encouraging us and reassuring us, Adriene! I recognized that I probably shouldn't have done day 1 since I'm very tired and sick, and have 0 energy, 0 strength. Still, I made it to the mat - which, like you always say, is the hardest thing to do. My mind was all over the place, as it always is; so many thoughts etc. Therefore, I recognize that I very easily get lost. I could not go into the 1st downward dog while pedaling the feet (the rest of the practice felt great, anyway!!!!): I recognized that my neck hurt and was too tense for me to even try and that is OKAY!!! I recognized that there can be bad, awful days but that good, happy days happen as well. I recognized that not everything is an end. Finally, I loved the "corpse pose" at the end, I felt calmer and proud for making it today. That feeling and the music made me feel like maybe, it's time for me to go back home. Maybe, I am at home; maybe, I finally feel at home. AND THAT'S A LOT TO TAKE FOR TODAY ONLY! haha.

I recognize my limitations so that I can work on them üôè There was a famous exchange between Bruce Lee and one of his students where the latter called the former lucky to be blessed with his talents, thus convincing himself that he could never achieve anything great. But Lee shared some of his many flaws that only he was aware of himself: his eyesight wasn't that great, one leg was shorter than the other, etc., and how he overcame them: hr started using contacts so that he appeared more like an action hero in movies (getting a role as Chinese man, let alone a leading role, was unheard of back then because of all the racism and sterotypes) he used his longer leg as his leading leg in fights, and all of his rejection to fuel his ambition of being one of the highest and most popular action actors of all time.

I noticed that one of the limitations that I kept glossing over is that my hands have trouble touching the ground evenly in the low lunges. For some reason today, I was like "why don't I just use the blocks?" You've always mentioned that if you can't reach the Earth, that you can always bring it up to you; and so I did that and I felt an amazing stretch! Here's to continuing to work hard and smart with no ego üí™ Sometimes the ego is there but I don't realize it until later. Namaste üôè

P.S. You were awesome on the Today Show! I tuned in on IG live to support and ended up joining you and Harry Styles in the flow as an inadvertent warm up to this practice. üåù

I've followed the January journeys since Revolution and each year I've vowed to try to keep up a regular practice throughout the rest of the year. Successes have varied but last year was the worst. I haven't done yoga for months. It's been a difficult time with stressful responsibilities and I couldn't get myself to show up on the mat.
I've never cried during yoga, but today I did. Right at the beginning, sitting cross-legged, left hand on the ground and right hand reaching up and over. I felt my side stretch and it screamed at me "this is what you needed" and realised I haven't felt a release of tension for way too long. I've been neglecting myself in the false name of productivity. What I needed wasn't to sit at my desk for a few hours more, trying to work. What I needed was to remember that I have a body and it needs me just as much as I need it. I have to take care of it if I want to succeed.
With tear-streaked cheeks and a smile I say namaste, Adriene. You are my angel.

This day's theme was pretty relevant to me, though maybe in a different way I had expected. After maybe 1,5 months of daily practice, I was excited to finally partake on my first 30-day yoga experience. But... I've been having some hip issues recently and consequently spent the last 24 hours reading about yoga injuries and hip safety. I learned a lot, though a lot of it is still all tangled up in my head :D. To be honest, I was nervous to practice today, in the fear of further damaging my body. So I approached this practice with the maximum mindfulness, truly trying to recognise my limits, find stability and apply the things I had learned. In my case that meant staying active in my body (a little micro movement going on all the time), not overdoing the movements even in the slightest & letting my shoulders rose naturally and steering away from that hip opener (I let my knees fall in instead).  I hope in time I can make these things normal for me that I can again concentrate more on what Adriene's saying haha. Take care of yourself everyone!
